aptac test suite
================

CI-ONLY. These tests run the REAL pacman / checkupdates / paccache / pactree /
reflector: they install and remove packages, refresh the files database, and
force-sync mirrors. Run them in the disposable CI container (Arch, root), never
on a real host -- they will mutate it. The workflow installs the deps
(pacman-contrib, reflector) and a synced db before running.

git-style harness. Each t[0-9]*.sh sources test-lib.sh, which fronts each real
tool with a thin wrapper: it appends the tool's argv to a per-script call log,
then execs the real binary. So every command genuinely runs, and the tests can
still assert WHICH underlying command aptac issued (the 1:1 header -> flag map)
via grep_call, on top of checking the real effect (e.g. install then pacman -Q).

Run (inside CI, or a throwaway Arch root container):
    sh t/run.sh                    # all scripts, PASS/FAIL with counts
    sh t/run.sh -v                 # also dump each script's full log inline
    (cd t && prove ./t[0-9]*.sh)   # TAP via prove, if installed
    (cd t && sh t0200-list.sh)     # a single script

Writing a test:
    test_expect_success 'desc' '
        reset_calls &&                       # clear the log right before...
        aptac --no-color install tree --noconfirm &&
        grep_call "pacman -S" &&             # ...asserting the issued flag
        pacman -Q tree                       # ...and the real effect
    '

Helpers: aptac, reset_calls, grep_call, test_must_fail, test_cmp,
test_when_finished. The call logger records pacman calls the test itself makes
too, so reset_calls immediately before the aptac invocation under test. Small
real packages used: tree (install/uninstall/orphs), bash (queries).
